title: Pacific Raceways Women's Road Racing Skills Clinic
description:
Women’s Clinic/Simulation Race Day
Feb. 20th, 2016

9:30AM Registration & Check-in
Clinic from 10:00AM - 2:00PM

Location: Pacific Raceways
course:
Join other female cyclists for a one day road racing skills and simulation racing clinic. This clinic is intended for new Cat 4 women to learn what it takes to race on the road and come away with more confidence through practice and race simulations. Cat 3 women are also encouraged to attend and brush up on skills plus learn some new ones. 

Come out to learn a variety of road racing skills:

-- Cornering
-- Contact/bumping
-- Sprinting
-- Pack riding & pacelining 

Located in Kent, Pacific Raceways is a car race track where you can learn in a safe, controlled environment. We rent out the track for the day, so you can practice without cars in your way.
registration: A 2016 USA Cycling annual license is required or you will need to purchase a one day license for $10
directions:
Pacific Raceways
31001 144th Ave SE, Kent, WA 98042

Google map for directions: https://goo.gl/maps/ZVKhz9EAaUP2

title: Ronde Van Palouse
description: Description: Ronde van Palouse (Tour of the Palouse) is a road race held in the spirit of the Spring Classics.  This is a Washington State BARR Senior event.
course: The course consists of a 16-mile circuit in the farm country near Spangle, Washington. The loop features 10 miles of good pavement and 6 miles of graded gravel. The constant rollers and the nearly constant wind of the Palouse make this a challenging circuit that favors the strongest all-around riders. The finish line is about two miles northeast of Liberty Middle School.
registration:
•	Entrance Fee:
o	Preregistration $35 includes sales tax, insurance surcharges, and USAC registration fees.
o	Day of Registration $45 includes sales tax, insurance surcharges, and registration fees.
•	Registration:  Online registration available at usacycling.org.  Day-of registration will be available. Check-in and registration is from 8 to 10:30 a.m. in the Liberty Middle School parking lot.  WSBA number required. $10 rental numbers available ($5 refundable for Wash. and Idaho residents; $10 refundable for all others).  USA Cycling license required. $10 One-Day Licenses available only for Men Cat 5 and Women Cat 4, no exceptions.
notes:
•	Host Housing—we will have a limited amount of host housing on Friday night for out of town racers.  Contact Jed Bardon at jedbardon@gmail.com
Frequently Asked Questions: 
•	Support vehicle for each field will be “wheels in-wheels out”.  However, your best bet is to run a wider tire with max air pressure.
•	A feed zone is available for teams and individuals with their own support person. Your soigneur should be instructed to stand in the feed zone on South Rattlers Run (see map below). There is parking at the intersection of Dawson Road and Rattlers Run Road. 
•	Award ceremony and will be at Liberty Middle School after the last field has finished (approximately 2:30 pm)
•	Timing provided by GC Racing
directions: •	Driving Directions: From Spokane, go 17 miles south on Hwy 195. Exit the highway left on East Cheney-Spangle Road. This is the second Spangle exit. You'll see the Harvester Restaurant to the left and a gas station on the right as you enter the town of Spangle. Continue to the stop sign at Main/Old 195. Turn right on Old SR 195 and proceed south for approximately one mile. Turn left on Spangle-Waverly Road. Proceed 3.5 miles to the staging area at Liberty Middle School on the right.

title: INWCX Series #5 - Liberty Lake Lunacy
description: Race #5 in the Inland Northwest Cyclocross Series. Liberty Lake Lunacy is held in Liberty Lake Regional Park.
course: The course includes grass, dirt, gravel, and beach sand (including dipping your wheels wet). Lots of twisty-turny, some long straight stretches, and one tough run-up (who's going to ride it this year?).

title: Walters Apple Cross
description: Cyclocross race that is one in a series of seven put on by organizer EMDE Sports.
course: Race course is at Walter's Fruit Ranch in Mead, WA.  Course is in and around an apple orchard and consists of varying terrain and is a circuit that meats USA cycling requirements for length, width, roll call zone, starting stretch and finishing line.
